---
import PageLayout from "../layouts/PageLayout.astro";

// This page is intentionally not linked in navigation
// It serves as internal documentation for thesis committee review
export const prerender = true;
---

<PageLayout 
  title="Site Guide" 
  currentPage="site-guide"
  description="Internal site guide describing how the John Crow Project is structured, how data flows, and how core interpretive systems work."
>
  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6 text-base-content">Site Guide</h1>
    
    <p class="text-lg text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-6">
      This site guide explains how the John Crow Project is organized: where its data comes from, how records and articles are generated, 
      how maps and charts are built, and how guided docent tours connect evidence to argument. It is written for committee members, 
      collaborators, and future maintainers rather than a general public audience.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-lg p-4 mb-8 not-prose">
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-1">
        <strong>Audience.</strong> Internal documentation for the dissertation committee, collaborators, and maintainers.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-0">
        <strong>Scope.</strong> High-level architecture, data sources, and key interpretive systems (maps, charts, and digital docent tours).
      </p>
    </div>

    <nav class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-5 mb-10 shadow-sm not-prose">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-vintage-ink">Table of contents</h2>
      <ul class="text-sm text-base-content/90 space-y-2">
        <li><a href="#what-the-site-is-for" class="text-accent hover:underline">• What the site is for</a></li>
        <li><a href="#core-architecture" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Core architecture</a></li>
        <li><a href="#data-model-and-sources" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Data model and sources</a></li>
        <li><a href="#maps-charts-and-spatial-workflow" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Maps, charts, and spatial workflow</a></li>
        <li><a href="#digital-docent-system" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Digital Docent system</a></li>
        <li><a href="#accessibility-and-maintenance" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Accessibility and maintenance</a></li>
        <li><a href="#future-direction" class="text-accent hover:underline">• Future direction</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>

    <h2 id="what-the-site-is-for" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      1. What the site is for
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      John Crow is both a research archive and an interpretive digital history project. It documents anti-Chinese violence in the United States, 
      roughly 1850–1915, and serves as a companion to the dissertation by making sources, data, and argument accessible in one place.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Research archive.</strong> Structured records of lethal violence, with metadata and links to newspaper sources.</li>
      <li><strong>Interpretive project.</strong> Maps, charts, and guided tours that make explicit claims about patterns, scale, and meaning.</li>
      <li><strong>Dissertation companion.</strong> A public interface that supports and extends the written thesis.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      Core public-facing components include:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Lynching Records.</strong> Case pages that combine structured fields (date, location, event type, victims) with a narrative synthesis and linked sources.</li>
      <li><strong>News Clips.</strong> Article-centric views of digitized newspaper scans and transcripts.</li>
      <li><strong>Dataset.</strong> A live, filterable table of lethal incidents, exportable as CSV/Excel/PDF.</li>
      <li><strong>Maps and Charts.</strong> Visualizations that show incidents, victims, categories, and slogans over time and space.</li>
      <li><strong>Ask the Archive.</strong> An AI-assisted interface that answers questions using the records and articles as context.</li>
      <li><strong>Guided Tours & Digital Docent.</strong> Step-based walkthroughs that model how evidence supports historical argument.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="core-architecture" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      2. Core architecture
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The site is an Astro application deployed to Netlify, with a thin layer of JavaScript for interactive components. 
      Styling is handled by Tailwind CSS plus a small set of custom classes that create the vintage newspaper aesthetic.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Astro site.</strong> Pages and layouts are written in Astro, with a few client-side islands where interactivity is required.</li>
      <li><strong>Styling.</strong> Tailwind CSS and custom CSS provide the typographic system, grid, and “aged paper and ink” palette.</li>
      <li><strong>Interactive components.</strong> ECharts powers charts; Mapbox GL + Turf power maps; React is used sparingly where a component benefits from stateful interaction.</li>
      <li><strong>Data access.</strong> A shared utility reads CSV/JSON exports from Google Sheets and exposes them via simple API routes.</li>
      <li><strong>Deployment.</strong> Netlify builds the Astro site, runs pre-build data sync scripts, and serves the final output over a global CDN.</li>
      <li><strong>Docent manifests.</strong> A dedicated API route builds docent tour manifests from Google Sheets CSV exports; static YAML manifests remain as a fallback.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-lg p-4 mb-10 not-prose">
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-1">
        <strong>Live vs. built data.</strong> Most user-facing content is driven by Google Sheets. Build-time scripts generate JSON snapshots for performance, 
        but key views (records, dataset, maps, charts, docent tours) can read fresh data via lightweight API routes when needed.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="data-model-and-sources" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      3. Data model and sources
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The project treats Google Sheets as the canonical source for both structured data and many narrative/label fields. 
      From there, the site materializes records, articles, charts, and docent steps.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3 text-base-content">Lynching records</h3>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      Each record combines structured fields from a “Main” tab (date, year, state, county, city, event type, number of victims, etc.) with a narrative summary 
      and links to article IDs. During build, data is synced into JSON; at runtime, the record routes and API endpoints read from that structured data.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3 text-base-content">News clips and article scans</h3>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      A separate sheet holds article metadata (publication, date, page, headline, violence category, related record ID, and file paths). 
      These rows drive the News Clips page and article viewer, which surface scans from <code>public/article-scans/</code> along with machine-readable transcripts.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      The News Clips route is designed to be query-parameter friendly (for example, filtered by entity or record) so that maps, records, and docent steps can link directly into article views.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3 text-base-content">Dataset table</h3>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      The Dataset page reads from the same lynching master sheet and presents a “living” table. Users can sort and filter in the browser and export the current view as CSV, Excel, or PDF. 
      This table is intended as the primary entry point for researchers who want to work with the full dataset rather than individual narratives.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3 text-base-content">Docent tours: tours and steps sheets</h3>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      The Digital Docent system is driven by two Google Sheets tabs:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-3 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>docent_tours.</strong> One row per tour (tour ID, title, subtitle, start route, start anchor, desktop-only flag, enabled flag, sort order).</li>
      <li><strong>docent_steps.</strong> One row per step (tour ID, step number, route, anchor/scroll target, optional highlight target and style, optional action, map focus ring, title, body text, enabled flag).</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-8">
      A backend helper reads these CSV exports and constructs a manifest for each tour. If the sheet-based manifest is unavailable or empty, 
      the system can fall back to local YAML manifests in <code>public/docents/</code> for legacy tours.
    </p>

    <h2 id="maps-charts-and-spatial-workflow" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      4. Maps, charts, and spatial workflow
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Maps and charts are central to the interpretive argument rather than decorative illustrations. They expose patterns in incidents, victims, 
      categories of violence, and slogans across time and space.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Charts.</strong> ECharts-based views show annual incidents and victims, state-level distributions, event types, pretexts, and Chinese population context.</li>
      <li><strong>Maps.</strong> Mapbox-based maps plot incidents and, in separate views, the geography of “Hong Di” reporting and “Chinese must go” mentions.</li>
      <li><strong>Record–map linkage.</strong> Records know their coordinates and can be focused on the map; the map, in turn, links back into individual record pages.</li>
      <li><strong>Workflow.</strong> Custom export scripts transform the lynching master sheet into chart-ready and map-ready JSON/tiles, 
        using AI-assisted coding to rapidly prototype and refine historical GIS interfaces.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-8">
      The goal is to let users move fluidly between narrative, table, chart, and map views, seeing the same incidents through different analytical lenses.
    </p>

    <h2 id="digital-docent-system" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      5. Digital Docent system
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The Digital Docent is a guided, step-based tour system that can move across records, articles, maps, charts, and filtered views. 
      Each step specifies where to send the reader, what to highlight, and what interpretive point to make.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Step-based manifests.</strong> For a given tour ID, the manifest includes an ordered list of steps with route, anchor/scrollTarget, optional highlight selector, and optional actions (for example, open a specific article).</li>
      <li><strong>Cross-page navigation.</strong> Steps can move from a record page into the map, into News Clips filtered by a record ID, or down into a particular chart section.</li>
      <li><strong>Highlighting.</strong> On desktop, the docent sidebar highlights the relevant text block, chart title, or map region to keep the user oriented.</li>
      <li><strong>Sheet-driven configuration.</strong> All of this behavior is configured row-by-row in the Google Sheets tabs mentioned above, so tours can be revised without touching code.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-lg p-4 mb-8 not-prose">
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-1">
        <strong>Quick Start vs. Docent Tours.</strong> The Quick Start tour teaches visitors how to use the site (navigation, filters, map controls). 
        The longer Digital Docent tours are interpretive walkthroughs that model how the dissertation reads the archive: following a case, 
        tracking how a lynching circulates in print, or situating incidents within broader patterns.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-0">
        At present, docent tours are desktop-oriented and require a reasonably wide viewport; on small screens, the sidebar is intentionally disabled.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="accessibility-and-maintenance" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      6. Accessibility and maintenance
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      Accessibility has been a first-order concern throughout the project. The public-facing statement at <code>/accessibility</code> 
      summarizes the commitment and documents WCAG 2.2 Level AA conformance.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Public statement.</strong> See <code>/accessibility</code> for a plain-language description of accessibility features and standards.</li>
      <li><strong>Audit details.</strong> The Git repository contains a more detailed accessibility audit report in <code>docs/reviews/accessibility-audit-2026.md</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Operations & setup.</strong> Additional maintenance documentation (Google Sheets setup, Apps Script integration, data/asset workflows, testing) lives under <code>docs/</code> in the repo.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-lg p-4 mb-10 not-prose">
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/90 mb-1">
        <strong>Maintenance note.</strong> When changing data structures or docent configurations, update the relevant docs in <code>docs/setup/</code>, 
        <code>docs/operations/</code>, or <code>docs/reviews/</code> so this guide and the repository remain in sync.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="future-direction" class="text-3xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-base-content border-b-2 border-amber-300 pb-2">
      7. Future direction
    </h2>

    <p class="text-base-content/90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      The site is stable and production-ready, but it is also intentionally unfinished. The underlying archive and interpretive frame will continue to evolve.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 text-base-content/90 space-y-1">
      <li><strong>Docent tours.</strong> Additional tours may foreground different themes (labor, law, print networks) or audiences (students, researchers, public history partners).</li>
      <li><strong>Data refinement.</strong> Ongoing work includes cleaning, extending, and re-coding incidents, as well as reconciling duplicate or marginal cases.</li>
      <li><strong>New cases and articles.</strong> As research continues, new records and newspaper clips can be added via the same Google Sheets pipeline.</li>
      <li><strong>Pedagogy.</strong> Future features may include classroom-facing modules, annotated paths, or comparative views that connect this archive to other racial violence datasets.</li>
    </ul>

